107
00:07:18,940 --> 00:07:20,920
Their motion is non-relativistic.

108
00:07:20,920 --> 00:07:21,680
What does pressure come from?

109
00:07:21,680 --> 00:07:24,500
Well, pressure comes from particles hitting the walls of a system.

110
00:07:24,500 --> 00:07:31,180
If we were just to think about a simple ordinary gas in a volume of space, pressure comes just

111
00:07:31,180 --> 00:07:34,760
by particles hitting the wall.

112
00:07:34,760 --> 00:07:38,460
It's proportional or related to the velocity of the particles that hit the wall.

113
00:07:38,460 --> 00:07:39,880
It contains the mass.

114
00:07:39,880 --> 00:07:40,880
Mass is important.

115
00:07:40,880 --> 00:07:45,260
If a bowling ball hits the wall, it creates a bigger force on the wall than if a ping

116
00:07:45,260 --> 00:07:47,080
pong ball does.

117
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:50,580
But whatever is hitting the wall, it's hitting the wall slowly.

118
00:07:50,580 --> 00:07:51,580
Because all the energy is going to the wall.

119
00:07:51,580 --> 00:07:56,480
So all of these particles are moving slowly, which means the pressure does not contain

120
00:07:56,480 --> 00:07:59,260
the speed of light in the formula for it.

121
00:07:59,260 --> 00:08:00,260
What does it contain?

122
00:08:00,260 --> 00:08:03,820
It contains the velocities of particles instead.

123
00:08:03,820 --> 00:08:10,180
And because it doesn't contain the speed of light, typically the pressure is much, much

124
00:08:10,180 --> 00:08:14,080
smaller for ordinary non-relativistic particles.

125
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:18,600
Much much smaller than the energy density.

126
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:20,260
That's the approximation that...

127
00:08:20,260 --> 00:08:21,260
Okay.

128
00:08:21,580 --> 00:08:29,460
So the pressure is approximately zero compared to the energy density, and that corresponds

129
00:08:29,460 --> 00:08:32,540
