00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:28,580
But the volume of the box is proportional to the cube.

249
00:16:28,580 --> 00:16:35,000
If we imagine, I did this problem by expanding the box along one axis.

250
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:41,520
But you could expand the box uniformly along all the axes and you get exactly the same thing.

251
00:16:41,520 --> 00:16:45,000
It was not important that the volume increased by only increasing

252
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,600
one dimension here.

253
00:16:46,600 --> 00:16:50,040
We could have increased it isotropically.

254
00:16:50,040 --> 00:16:51,040
Same equation here.

255
00:16:51,040 --> 00:16:57,580
And if we increase the box isotropically, we can think of it that the volume of the

256
00:16:57,580 --> 00:17:02,700
box is proportional to the cube of the scale factor.

257
00:17:02,700 --> 00:17:07,980
The volume of a box of space is proportional to the cube of the scale factor.

258
00:17:07,980 --> 00:17:13,380
And so that is equal to some constant, which we can call rho-naught, but I'll just call

259
00:17:13,380 --> 00:17:14,380
it constant.

260
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:21,980
divided by the scale factor, cubed, to the 1 plus w.

261
00:17:21,980 --> 00:17:22,980
Why cubed?

262
00:17:22,980 --> 00:17:26,060
Because the volume is the scale factor cubed.

263
00:17:26,060 --> 00:17:35,800
If you're one of these crazy people who likes to do cosmology in different numbers of dimensions,

264
00:17:35,800 --> 00:17:41,000
then this cubed could become the fourth power, it could become the second power and so forth.

265
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:43,520
But otherwise it would be the same.

266
00:17:43,520 --> 00:17:44,720
Uh...

267
00:17:44,720 --> 00:17:51,880
But if you're a sensible three-dimensional person, this is the formula, and this formula

268
00:17:51,880 --> 00:17:53,480
now is famous.

269
00:17:53,480 --> 00:18:03,080
Okay, let's just remind ourselves again, for matter dominated, where the pressure is almost

270
00:18:03,080 --> 00:18:08,780
zero, because things are moving slowly, where the pressure is almost zero, that corresponds

271
00:18:08,780 --> 00:18:12,340
to w equals zero.

272
00:18:12,340 --> 00:18:15,680
Pressure is equal to zero times the energy density.

273
00:18:15,680 --> 00:18:23,320
In that case, we just get rho goes like one over a cubed, and that's this formula over

274
00:18:23,320 --> 00:18:25,740
here.

275
00:18:25,740 --> 00:18:32,320
For radiation, which I simply told you the answer for, but we'll work it out tonight,

276
00:18:32,320 --> 00:18:36,940
for radiation, w is equal to a third.

277
00:18:36,940 --> 00:18:42,280
If w is equal to a third, then one plus w is four thirds.

278
00:18:42,280 --> 00:18:47,460
And this becomes a constant over a to the fourth.

279
00:18:47,460 --> 00:18:53,420
One plus w is four thirds, times three is just four, four thirds times three is four,

280
00:18:53,420 --> 00:18:58,580
and we get one over a to the fourth.

281
00:18:58,580 --> 00:19:02,640
So okay, that was review.

282
00:19:02,640 --> 00:19:11,580
Now let's come to the question of why w is equal to a third for radiation.

283
00:19:11,580 --> 00:19:14,480
Radiation is massless particles.

284
00:19:14,480 --> 00:19:16,540
Radiation means photons.

285
00:19:16,540 --> 00:19:20,300
We could think of it also as electromagnetic waves.

286
00:19:20,300 --> 00:19:23,180
We would get the same answer, incidentally.

287
00:19:23,180 --> 00:19:25,700
But let's think of it as photons.

288
00:19:25,700 --> 00:19:33,920
The characteristic feature of photons that makes it different than the non-relativistic

289
00:19:33,920 --> 00:19:38,140
matter is that the photons are moving fast, and in fact, they're moving with the speed

290
00:19:38,140 --> 00:19:39,060
of light.

291
00:19:39,060 --> 00:19:40,060
Okay.

292
00:19:40,060 --> 00:19:40,900
So let's work.

293
00:19:40,900 --> 00:19:41,400
Okay.

294
00:19:41,580 --> 00:19:43,400
Let's work out the equation of state.

295
00:19:43,400 --> 00:19:44,400
Let's work it out.

296
00:19:44,400 --> 00:19:47,120
We're going to work it out in detail.

297
00:19:47,120 --> 00:19:52,120
The equation of state for a box filled with photons.

298
00:19:52,120 --> 00:19:54,500
Here's our box.

299
00:19:54,500 --> 00:19:57,700
It's three-dimensional, but I'm not good at drawing three-dimensional boxes, so we'll

300
00:19:57,700 --> 00:20:00,220
just draw a two-dimensional box.

301
00:20:00,220 --> 00:20:04,880
And it's filled uniformly with lots of photons.

302
00:20:04,880 --> 00:20:10,500
And of course, this is an instantaneous picture of it, but the photons are whizzing around

303
00:20:10,500 --> 00:20:11,500
with the speed of light.

304
00:20:11,580 --> 00:20:16,700
So what's more, they're bouncing off the walls.

305
00:20:16,700 --> 00:20:18,820
They're bouncing off the walls.

306
00:20:18,820 --> 00:20:27,480
We'll assume that when they bounce off the walls, they bounce off and lose no energy

307
00:20:27,480 --> 00:20:31,000
and exert pressure on the walls.

308
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:35,640
We need to know a couple of things, all of which I think we've talked about in the past.

309
00:20:35,640 --> 00:20:36,240
Uh...

310
00:20:36,240 --> 00:20:36,740
Uh...

311
00:20:36,740 --> 00:20:37,240
Uh...

312
00:20:37,240 --> 00:20:37,740
Uh...

313
00:20:37,740 --> 00:20:38,240
Uh...

314
00:20:38,240 --> 00:20:38,740
Uh...

315
00:20:38,740 --> 00:20:39,240
Uh...

316
00:20:39,240 --> 00:20:39,740
Uh...

317
00:20:39,740 --> 00:20:40,240
Uh...

318
00:20:40,240 --> 00:20:40,740
Uh...

319
00:20:40,740 --> 00:20:41,240
Uh...

320
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:41,540
Uh...

321
00:20:41,540 --> 00:20:41,580
Uh...

322
00:20:41,580 --> 00:20:42,080
Uh...

323
00:20:42,080 --> 00:20:42,580
Uh...

324
00:20:42,580 --> 00:20:44,900
First of all, photons have energy.

325
00:20:44,900 --> 00:20:45,420
Let's call...

326
00:20:45,420 --> 00:20:47,700
What I'm going to do is pretend.

327
00:20:47,700 --> 00:20:50,340
But then I'll tell you why it didn't matter.

328
00:20:50,340 --> 00:20:54,820
I'm going to pretend all of the photons have the same energy.

329
00:20:54,820 --> 00:21:00,680
Now, for a box of photons in thermal equilibrium, it's approximately true as a matter of fact

330
00:21:00,680 --> 00:21:03,300
that they all have roughly the same energy.

331
00:21:03,300 --> 00:21:07,160
But nothing I'm doing really depends on that, and we'll see why.

332
00:21:07,160 --> 00:21:11,380
But for the moment, let's just pretend they all have the same energy.

333
00:21:11,380 --> 00:21:18,380
Let's call the energy per photon or per particle, let's call it epsilon.

334
00:21:18,380 --> 00:21:21,620
I'm not calling it epsilon with any deep motive.

335
00:21:21,620 --> 00:21:24,380
Often epsilon is used for a small number.

336
00:21:24,380 --> 00:21:28,240
Well, the energy of a photon is a small number, but that's not why I used it.

337
00:21:28,240 --> 00:21:33,080
I used it because it looks like E, but I want to save E for the total energy.

338
00:21:33,080 --> 00:21:38,340
So epsilon is the energy per particle or energy per photon.

339
00:21:38,340 --> 00:21:40,180
Uh...

340
00:21:40,180 --> 00:21:41,340
Energy...

341
00:21:41,340 --> 00:21:46,460
Per photon.

342
00:21:46,460 --> 00:21:49,020
On the average.

343
00:21:49,020 --> 00:21:50,980
What about the momentum of a proton?

344
00:21:50,980 --> 00:21:51,980
We're going to need the momentum.

345
00:21:51,980 --> 00:21:54,080
Why do we need the momentum?

346
00:21:54,080 --> 00:21:59,820
Because forces, what forces are, is their response to the change of momentum.

347
00:21:59,820 --> 00:22:06,460
If I throw a tennis ball at the wall, the tennis ball has some momentum.

348
00:22:06,460 --> 00:22:09,340
When it reflects back, it has the opposite momentum.

349
00:22:09,340 --> 00:22:10,900
There's been a change of momentum.

350
00:22:10,900 --> 00:22:16,020
There's also been a transfer of momentum to the wall.

351
00:22:16,020 --> 00:22:20,940
That transfer of momentum per unit time...

352
00:22:20,940 --> 00:22:24,820
Transfer of momentum per unit time is the force on the wall.

353
00:22:24,820 --> 00:22:30,960
So we need to know something about the momenta of photons.

354
00:22:30,960 --> 00:22:35,140
The momentum of a photon I normally would call P.

355
00:22:35,140 --> 00:22:39,960
The problem with P is I'm already using P for pressure.

356
00:22:39,960 --> 00:22:40,900
So we're running into the...

357
00:22:40,900 --> 00:22:48,020
This problem that the number of letters of the alphabet is bounded by 26.

358
00:22:48,020 --> 00:22:51,900
Therefore I use Greek letters.

359
00:22:51,900 --> 00:22:54,460
The momentum of a photon I'm going to call pi.

360
00:22:54,460 --> 00:22:58,320
It is not 3.14159.

361
00:22:58,320 --> 00:23:02,740
It's just the momentum of a particle and it's a little vector.

362
00:23:02,740 --> 00:23:03,740
It's a vector.

363
00:23:03,740 --> 00:23:05,960
It has three components.

364
00:23:05,960 --> 00:23:09,900
That's the momentum of a characteristic particle in there.

365
00:23:09,900 --> 00:23:10,900
Uh...

366
00:23:10,900 --> 00:23:14,280
Of course the momentum could be in any direction.

367
00:23:14,280 --> 00:23:19,220
And one of the assumptions is if I look in any little volume of the box,

368
00:23:19,220 --> 00:23:23,820
on the average the momentum could be in any direction.

369
00:23:23,820 --> 00:23:27,480
That if I look at the velocity or momentum distribution,

370
00:23:27,480 --> 00:23:30,040
anywhere's in the box it's isotropic.

371
00:23:30,040 --> 00:23:33,280
As many particles going in every direction as in every other direction.

372
00:23:33,280 --> 00:23:34,940
And that's a good assumption.

373
00:23:34,940 --> 00:23:39,900
That's a fair assumption that can be justified using statistical mechanics.

374
00:23:40,900 --> 00:23:42,180
Alright, so pi...

375
00:23:42,180 --> 00:23:44,480
The vector pi is the momentum.

376
00:23:44,480 --> 00:23:52,000
The magnitude of the momentum we can just call pi or put some bars around it.

377
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:55,820
The magnitude of it or the absolute value of it is just called pi.

378
00:23:55,820 --> 00:23:59,980
It's the magnitude of the vector pi.

379
00:23:59,980 --> 00:24:05,080
And the relationship between the energy of a particle and its momentum,

380
00:24:05,080 --> 00:24:09,900
if I keep around the speed of light, then the energy of a massless particle, a photon,

381
00:24:09,900 --> 00:24:10,900
will be the energy.

382
00:24:10,900 --> 00:24:17,900
The energy of a massless particle, a photon, is equal to the speed of light times the magnitude of the momentum.

383
00:24:17,900 --> 00:24:19,900
Whoops, not p.

384
00:24:19,900 --> 00:24:21,900
Not p.

385
00:24:21,900 --> 00:24:23,900
Pi.

386
00:24:23,900 --> 00:24:30,900
Instead of writing the bars, I'm not going to write the bars, I'm just going to write pi.

387
00:24:30,900 --> 00:24:35,900
But when I mean the vector pi, I'll put a little vector symbol on top.

388
00:24:35,900 --> 00:24:39,900
So pi is the magnitude of the momentum.

389
00:24:39,900 --> 00:24:42,900
Equals momentum of a particle.

390
00:24:42,900 --> 00:24:46,900
Times c.

391
00:24:46,900 --> 00:24:49,900
Energy is pi times c.

392
00:24:49,900 --> 00:24:54,900
That's the relationship between the energy of a massless particle and its momentum.

393
00:24:54,900 --> 00:24:58,900
And since we set c equal to one,

394
00:24:58,900 --> 00:25:03,900
the energy is just the magnitude of the momentum.

395
00:25:03,900 --> 00:25:08,900
Next, what about the number of particles,

396
00:25:08,900 --> 00:25:11,900
the number of photons in the box?

397
00:25:11,900 --> 00:25:14,900
And better yet, the number density.

398
00:25:14,900 --> 00:25:18,900
Let's let nu, nu for number,

399
00:25:18,900 --> 00:25:26,900
let nu be the number of particles, number of photons,

400
00:25:26,900 --> 00:25:29,900
per unit volume.

401
00:25:29,900 --> 00:25:32,900
The density of photons.

402
00:25:32,900 --> 00:25:33,900
It's not the density of energy.

403
00:25:33,900 --> 00:25:36,900
What is the density of energy in this language?

404
00:25:38,900 --> 00:25:43,900
The energy per particle times the number of particles.

405
00:25:43,900 --> 00:25:46,900
So epsilon times nu would be rho.

406
00:25:46,900 --> 00:25:47,900
We'll come back to that.

407
00:25:47,900 --> 00:25:49,900
Epsilon times nu would be rho.

408
00:25:52,900 --> 00:25:55,900
Let's calculate the pressure now.

409
00:25:55,900 --> 00:26:01,900
To calculate the pressure, we have to have a proper theory of what pressure is.

410
00:26:01,900 --> 00:26:09,900
So here's the walls of a hypothetical box.

411
00:26:09,900 --> 00:26:11,900
That's a wall.

412
00:26:11,900 --> 00:26:13,900
The boundary of a box.

413
00:26:13,900 --> 00:26:15,900
The gas is on the left side of the box,

414
00:26:15,900 --> 00:26:17,900
the gas of photons.

415
00:26:17,900 --> 00:26:21,900
And let's take a little volume here.

416
00:26:21,900 --> 00:26:23,900
I'll tell you what this is in a minute.

417
00:26:23,900 --> 00:26:26,900
Let's consider a little time interval, delta t.

418
00:26:26,900 --> 00:26:29,900
Take a little time interval, delta t.

419
00:26:29,900 --> 00:26:36,900
What I'm going to be interested in is how many particles hit the boundary of the box

420
00:26:36,900 --> 00:26:41,900
and transfer momentum to it in the time interval delta t.

421
00:26:41,900 --> 00:26:49,900
Now, the answer is a particle will hit the boundary in time delta t if it's close enough.

422
00:26:49,900 --> 00:26:53,900
Oh, incidentally, what's the velocity of these particles?

423
00:26:53,900 --> 00:26:54,900
One.

424
00:26:54,900 --> 00:26:55,900
One.

425
00:26:55,900 --> 00:26:56,900
C.

426
00:26:56,900 --> 00:26:57,900
Yeah, C.

427
00:26:57,900 --> 00:26:59,900
But we'll take it to be one.

428
00:26:59,900 --> 00:27:00,900
All right.

429
00:27:00,900 --> 00:27:04,900
If the particle is moving horizontally to the left,

430
00:27:04,900 --> 00:27:10,900
where does it have to be in here in order that it will hit the boundary within time delta t?

431
00:27:10,900 --> 00:27:12,900
And the answer is quite clear.

432
00:27:12,900 --> 00:27:23,900
If delta x is less than or if delta x is equal to delta t,

433
00:27:23,900 --> 00:27:26,900
and I make this little interval here, delta x,

434
00:27:26,900 --> 00:27:29,900
then any particle moving to the right,

435
00:27:29,900 --> 00:27:35,900
with horizontal velocity, will hit the wall in time delta t.

436
00:27:35,900 --> 00:27:38,900
But what if it's not quite moving to the right?

437
00:27:38,900 --> 00:27:41,900
What if it's moving at an angle theta?

438
00:27:41,900 --> 00:27:46,900
So let's take a particle moving at an angle theta.

439
00:27:46,900 --> 00:27:50,900
Then it will hit the wall of the box.

440
00:27:50,900 --> 00:27:56,900
Let me get the equation straight.

441
00:27:56,900 --> 00:28:03,900
If delta x is equal to delta t times cosine of the angle theta.

442
00:28:03,900 --> 00:28:06,900
If the cosine of the angle of theta is one,

443
00:28:06,900 --> 00:28:08,900
that means it's horizontal,

444
00:28:08,900 --> 00:28:11,900
then the particle will hit the corner of the wall of the box

445
00:28:11,900 --> 00:28:15,900
if it's within delta x equals delta t.

446
00:28:15,900 --> 00:28:18,900
On the other hand, supposing cosine theta,

447
00:28:18,900 --> 00:28:21,900
supposing theta is perpendicular, is vertical,

448
00:28:21,900 --> 00:28:24,900
supposing theta is 90 degrees,

449
00:28:24,900 --> 00:28:26,900
what's the cosine of 90 degrees?

450
00:28:26,900 --> 00:28:27,900
Zero.

451
00:28:27,900 --> 00:28:28,900
Zero.

452
00:28:28,900 --> 00:28:32,900
And that's of course correct if the particles are moving almost vertically,

453
00:28:32,900 --> 00:28:37,900
they will only hit the box if delta x is very small.

454
00:28:37,900 --> 00:28:42,900
They'll have to be very close to hit the box in time delta t.

455
00:28:42,900 --> 00:28:44,900
So this is the condition.

456
00:28:44,900 --> 00:28:49,900
All particles within a distance delta x will hit the wall of the box

457
00:28:49,900 --> 00:28:54,900
if delta x is equal to delta t times cosine theta.

458
00:28:54,900 --> 00:28:59,900
Now let's take particles moving at angle delta theta.

459
00:29:05,900 --> 00:29:08,900
Supposing one particle hits the wall of the box.

460
00:29:08,900 --> 00:29:12,900
How much momentum does it transfer,

461
00:29:12,900 --> 00:29:17,900
how much horizontal momentum does it transfer to the wall of the box?

462
00:29:17,900 --> 00:29:23,900
Well, the magnitude of the momentum is epsilon.

463
00:29:23,900 --> 00:29:29,900
Let's call this, yeah, let's say delta pi.

464
00:29:29,900 --> 00:29:32,900
The change in the x component, what we're thinking about now,

465
00:29:32,900 --> 00:29:36,900
is a particle which hits the wall and bounces off.

466
00:29:36,900 --> 00:29:40,900
And it transfers some x momentum to the wall.

467
00:29:40,900 --> 00:29:41,900
How much?

468
00:29:41,900 --> 00:29:47,900
Well, the magnitude of the momentum that it started with was epsilon.

469
00:29:47,900 --> 00:29:49,900
That's the magnitude of the momentum.

470
00:29:49,900 --> 00:29:52,900
Its component along the x-axis is epsilon cosine t.

471
00:29:52,900 --> 00:29:59,900
So that's the component of the momentum.

472
00:29:59,900 --> 00:30:03,900
And how much momentum is transferred?

473
00:30:03,900 --> 00:30:04,900
Twice that much.

474
00:30:04,900 --> 00:30:07,900
Why is it twice that much?

475
00:30:07,900 --> 00:30:10,900
Because it starts moving with a certain momentum,

476
00:30:10,900 --> 00:30:12,900
it bounces back,

477
00:30:12,900 --> 00:30:16,900
and the amount of change of momentum is twice its momentum.

478
00:30:16,900 --> 00:30:21,900
So the change in the momentum of that particle along the x-axis

479
00:30:21,900 --> 00:30:26,900
is twice epsilon cosine of theta.

480
00:30:26,900 --> 00:30:28,900
Now let's divide that by delta t.

481
00:30:28,900 --> 00:30:33,900
I'll tell you in a moment why we're dividing it by delta t.

482
00:30:33,900 --> 00:30:35,900
Oh, yeah, that's right.

483
00:30:35,900 --> 00:30:40,900
Twice epsilon cosine theta, let's divide it by delta t.

484
00:30:40,900 --> 00:30:43,900
Why am I dividing it by delta t?

485
00:30:43,900 --> 00:30:49,900
Because the force on the wall is the change of momentum per unit time,

486
00:30:49,900 --> 00:30:52,900
is the transfer of momentum per unit time.

487
00:30:52,900 --> 00:30:54,900
That's Newton's equations.

488
00:30:54,900 --> 00:30:59,900
The change, the force on an object is the time rate of change of its momentum.

489
00:30:59,900 --> 00:31:05,900
And so this is the force exerted for each particle that hits the wall.

490
00:31:05,900 --> 00:31:10,900
Twice epsilon cosine theta over delta t.

491
00:31:10,900 --> 00:31:15,900
Uh, good.

492
00:31:15,900 --> 00:31:18,900
Now, how do we find the full force?

493
00:31:18,900 --> 00:31:21,900
We have to calculate how many particles hit the wall.

494
00:31:21,900 --> 00:31:24,900
This is what we get per particle hitting the wall.

495
00:31:24,900 --> 00:31:26,900
How many particles hit the wall?

496
00:31:26,900 --> 00:31:33,900
How many particles moving at angle cosine theta hit the wall in a time delta t?

497
00:31:33,900 --> 00:31:41,900
Well, a particle will hit the wall if it's within delta x.

498
00:31:41,900 --> 00:31:45,900
How many of them are there within delta x?

499
00:31:45,900 --> 00:31:48,900
The answer is the number of particles,

500
00:31:48,900 --> 00:31:52,900
but the number of particles that will hit the wall in that time

501
00:31:52,900 --> 00:31:55,900
is going to be delta x

502
00:31:58,900 --> 00:32:02,900
times the area of the wall, times the area,

503
00:32:02,900 --> 00:32:05,900
that's the volume of this little region,

504
00:32:05,900 --> 00:32:11,900
times the number of particles per unit volume.

505
00:32:11,900 --> 00:32:16,900
n delta x, n equals

506
00:32:16,900 --> 00:32:22,900
delta x area times the number of particles.

507
00:32:22,900 --> 00:32:26,900
And, um, let's see, have I left anything out of this?

508
00:32:26,900 --> 00:32:30,900
Nothing.

509
00:32:30,900 --> 00:32:31,900
Okay.

510
00:32:31,900 --> 00:32:34,900
So we should multiply this by the number of particles

511
00:32:34,900 --> 00:32:37,900
that hit the wall in time delta t.

512
00:32:37,900 --> 00:32:44,900
And that's pressure will equal twice epsilon cosine theta

513
00:32:44,900 --> 00:32:50,900
divided by delta t times the number,

514
00:32:50,900 --> 00:32:58,900
which is delta x area number of particles per unit volume.

515
00:32:58,900 --> 00:33:06,900
But delta x is delta t cosine theta.

516
00:33:06,900 --> 00:33:12,900
So delta x over delta t is cosine theta.

517
00:33:12,900 --> 00:33:14,900
So we get a formula.

518
00:33:14,900 --> 00:33:18,900
The pressure due to particles moving at angle theta

519
00:33:18,900 --> 00:33:23,900
is twice epsilon cosine theta.

520
00:33:23,900 --> 00:33:28,900
Delta x over delta t is another factor of cosine theta,

521
00:33:28,900 --> 00:33:32,900
cosine squared theta times nu.

522
00:33:38,900 --> 00:33:40,900
There's one mistake in this formula,

523
00:33:40,900 --> 00:33:42,900
the factor of two.

524
00:33:42,900 --> 00:33:45,900
Why is there a mistake in the factor of two?

525
00:33:45,900 --> 00:33:47,900
And the answer is simple.

526
00:33:47,900 --> 00:33:51,900
A particle, if it's in here,

527
00:33:51,900 --> 00:33:53,900
and moving toward the right,

528
00:33:53,900 --> 00:33:55,900
will hit the wall.

529
00:33:55,900 --> 00:33:57,900
But one moving toward the left won't.

530
00:33:57,900 --> 00:34:01,900
So half the particles per unit volume

531
00:34:01,900 --> 00:34:04,900
are unavailable to hit the wall.

532
00:34:04,900 --> 00:34:07,900
Really, we should only count those particles

533
00:34:07,900 --> 00:34:09,900
whose x component of velocity

534
00:34:09,900 --> 00:34:11,900
is toward the wall.

535
00:34:11,900 --> 00:34:14,900
The other particles moving in the opposite direction

536
00:34:14,900 --> 00:34:16,900
are not going to hit the wall.

537
00:34:16,900 --> 00:34:19,900
So we've really overestimated by a factor of two,

538
00:34:19,900 --> 00:34:21,900
and that's correct, that is correct.

539
00:34:21,900 --> 00:34:24,900
We've overestimated by a factor of two

540
00:34:24,900 --> 00:34:27,900
because in putting in here the full

541
00:34:27,900 --> 00:34:31,900
number of particles per unit volume,

542
00:34:31,900 --> 00:34:33,900
I've put too many in.

543
00:34:33,900 --> 00:34:35,900
So we just wipe out the two here,

544
00:34:35,900 --> 00:34:37,900
and now we have a correct formula.

545
00:34:39,900 --> 00:34:43,900
Epsilon times nu, what is that?

546
00:34:46,900 --> 00:34:49,900
The energy per unit volume, or rho.

547
00:34:49,900 --> 00:34:51,900
We're getting there.

548
00:34:51,900 --> 00:34:54,900
The pressure is equal to the energy per unit volume,

549
00:34:54,900 --> 00:34:57,900
that's rho, times this cosine squared theta.

550
00:34:57,900 --> 00:34:59,900
Now wait a minute, what the hell did we do?

